                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d201">
                <head>No. 180.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">White</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Evarts</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1879-07-12">
                            <hi rend="italic">July</hi> 12, 1879</date>. (Received August
                        6.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 26.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Everything that I can learn from various
                    influential quarters here confirms the impression made upon me, * * * that
                    Germany will not sell any more silver, but that she will make reissues. I find
                    this to be the opinion of influential members of the German Parliament with whom
                    I have recently conversed, an opinion not born especially of hope, since it is
                    shared by many who are most opposed to the policy.</p>
                <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>AND. D. WHITE.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
